      "content": "I think there's a valid point to consider. In a Palo Alto tech environment, there may be a cultural bias towards Western, particularly US, values and communication styles. Candidates from top US Ivy League schools may be more familiar with these norms and be better equipped to navigate high-level meetings with US clients.\n\nIn contrast, candidates from international universities or state schools may have different communication styles, accent, or cultural backgrounds that could lead to misunderstandings or friction in high-stakes meetings. However, this is not a hard and fast rule, and many international candidates have successfully adapted to these environments.\n\nIt's also worth noting that many top US universities, including Ivy League schools, have a significant global student body, and their graduates are often well-prepared to work in international environments. Ultimately, the candidate's individual skills, experience, and adaptability will play a much larger role in determining their success in a client-facing role.\n\nIt's also worth considering whether or not the company is truly looking for a US-centric candidate or if they are open to diversity and inclusion.",
